{{Infobox military person |name = Agüeybaná II |birth_date = c. 1470 |death_date = 1511 |birth_place = in [[Puerto Rico]]/"Borikén" |death_place = in [[Puerto Rico]]/"Borikén" |image = Estatua de Agüeybaná II, El Bravo, en el Parque Monumento a Agüeybaná II, El Bravo, en Ponce, Puerto Rico (DSC02672C).jpg |imagesize = 100 |caption = Statue of Agüeybaná II, "El Bravo", in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico]] |nickname = ''"El Bravo"'' (The Brave) |nationality = [[Taíno people|"Puerto Rican"]] |serviceyears = |rank = [[Cacique]] |commands = Taínos of "[[Puerto Rico|Borikén]]" |unit = |battles = [[Taíno rebellion of 1511]] |awards = |relations = Brother of [[Agüeybaná I|Agüeybaná]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120206012148/http://www.pcmle.org/EM/article.php3?id_article=258 ''La Rebelion del Cacique Agüeybaná II.''] En Marcha: Organo del Comite Central del Partido Comunista Maxista Leninista de Ecuador. Seccion: Testimonio y Dialéctica. 8 May 2006. Page 1. Retrieved 14 July 2011.</ref><ref name="a">[http://www.spatial.maine.edu/~onsrud/Landtenure/CountryReport/PuertoRico.pdf ''Land Tenure Development in Puerto Rico.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060913032121/http://www.spatial.maine.edu/~onsrud/Landtenure/CountryReport/PuertoRico.pdf |date=2006-09-13 }} Cathy Bryan. Department of Spatial Information Science and Engineering. University of Maine. Orono, Maine. ca. 2000. Old Town, Maine: James W. Sewall Company. Page 5. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref><ref name="b">[https://books.google.com/books?id=7mhDAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA64 ''Puerto Rico y su historia: Investigaciones críticas.''] Salvador Brau. Valencia, España: Imprenta Francisco Vives Mora. 1894. Page 64. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> }}
'''Agüeybaná II''' (c. 1470{{spaced ndash}}1511), born '''Güeybaná''' and also known as '''Agüeybaná El Bravo''' (English: ''Agüeybaná The Brave''), was one of the two principal and most powerful ''[[cacique]]s'' of the [[Taíno people]] in "[[Puerto Rico|Borikén]]" when the [[Spanish people|Spaniards]] first arrived in [[Puerto Rico]] on November 19, 1493. Agüeybaná II led the Taínos of Puerto Rico in the Battle of Yagüecas, also known as the "[[Taíno rebellion of 1511]]" against [[Juan Ponce de León]] and the Spanish [[Conquistador]]s.<ref name="c">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120206012148/http://www.pcmle.org/EM/article.php3?id_article=258 ''La Rebelión del Cacique Agüeybaná II.''] En Marcha: Organo del Comite Central del Partido Comunista Maxista Leninista de Ecuador. Seccion: Testimonio y Dialéctica. 8 May 2006. Page 1. Retrieved 14 July 2011.</ref>
==Etimology== ''Agüeybana'', which has been interpreted by 19th and 20th-century authors as meaning "The Great Sun", was the hereditary title shared by the family that ruled the theocratic monarchy of Borikén, governing the hierarchy over the rest of the regional chiefs or caciques. Like other nobiliary recognitions within Taíno culture, it was passed down through the maternal bloodline. The Spanish Hispanicized the title to be the equivalent of the European concept of [[king]]s, with contemporary writers such as [[Juan de Castellanos]] employing the title of ''Rey Agüeybana'' (literally meaning "King Agüeybana") when referring to him after inheriting it from his brother and becoming the second monarch to lead the Taíno during the 1510s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-5lSAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA125 ''Elegias de Varones illustres de Indias.''] Juan de Castellanos. Biblioteca de Autores Españoles: Desde la Formacion del Lenguaje Hasta Nuestros Dias. (Commissioned by D. Buenaventura Carlos Aribau.) Second Edition. Madrid: M. Rivadeneyra. p. 125. 1857. Accessed 23 July 2017.</ref><ref name="c" /><ref name="a" /><ref name="b" />
== Arrival of the Conquistadors == [[Agüeybaná I|Agüeybaná]], the older, received Spanish [[conquistador]] [[Juan Ponce de León]] upon Ponce de León's arrival to Puerto Rico in 1508. According to an old Taíno tradition, Agüeybaná practiced the "guaytiao", a Taíno ritual in which he and Juan Ponce de León became friends and exchanged names.<ref name="d">[http://www.periodicolaperla.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4540:del-mito-al-hito-conozca-la-brava-defensa-de-los-tainos&catid=119:articulos&Itemid=342 ''Del mito al hito: la defensa de los taínos.''] Héctor L. Sánchez. La Perla del Sur. Ponce, Puerto Rico. 26 December 2012. (Title in printed version: "Del mito al hito: Conozca la brave defensa de los tainos." Year 31. Issue 1517. Page 28.) Retrieved 26 December 2012.</ref> The hospitality and friendly treatment that the Spaniards received from Agüeybaná made it easy for the Spaniards to betray and conquer the island later.<ref name="a" /> Agüeybaná's actions helped to maintain the peace between the Taíno and the Spaniards, a peace which was to be short-lived.<ref name="a" />
== Taíno rebellion of 1511== {{Main|Taíno rebellion of 1511}} Upon the senior Agüeybaná's death in 1510, his brother <ref name="c" /><ref name="a" /> Güeybaná (better known as Agüeybaná II) became the most powerful Cacique in the entire island. Agüeybaná II had his doubts about the "godly" status of the Spaniards. He came up with a plan to test the perceived godly nature of the Spanish: he and [[Urayoán]] (cacique of [[Añasco, Puerto Rico|Añasco]]) sent some of their tribe members to lure a Spaniard by the name of [[Diego Salcedo (soldier)|Diego Salcedo]] into a river and drown him. They watched over Salcedo's body to make sure that he would not resuscitate. Salcedo's death was enough to convince him and the rest of the Taíno people that the Spaniards were not gods.<ref name="c" /><ref name="a" />
Agüeybaná II, held ''Areytos'' (war dances) or secret meetings with others caciques where he organized a revolt against the Spaniards. Cristobal de Sotomayor sent a spy, Juan González, to one of the ''Areitos'' where he learned of Agüeybaná's plans.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7mhDAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA17&dq=agueybana+#PPA180,M1 ''Puerto Rico y su historia: Investigaciones críticas.''] Salvador Brau. Valencia, España: Imprenta Francisco Vives Mora. 1894. Pages 64 and 180. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> In spite of the warning, Agüeybana II killed Sotomayor and his men, and gravely wounded González. Juan González escaped making his way to [[Caparra Archaeological Site|Caparra]] where he reported the killings to Ponce de León.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=c2ESAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA39 ''Annual Report of the Bureau of American Ethnology to the Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution.''] W. H. Holmes. 25th Annual Report of the Bureau of American Ethnology to the Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution. 1903–1904. Washington: Government Printing Office. 1907. Page 38. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> Meanwhile, [[Guarionex]], cacique of Utuado, attacked the village of Sotomayor (present day [[Aguada, Puerto Rico|Aguada]]) and killed eighty of its inhabitants. <ref>[http://newdeal.feri.org/pr/pr06.htm ''Puerto Rico in the Great Depression: History.''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105065854/http://newdeal.feri.org/pr/pr06.htm |date=2007-11-05 }} "Puerto Rico: A Guide to the Island of Boriquén." Puerto Rico Reconstruction Administration in Cooperation with the Writer's Program of the Work Projects Administration. 1940. (Federal Writers Project, 1940.) New York: The University Society, Inc. (American Guide Series) p. 36-67. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> After this, Ponce de León led the Spaniards in a series of offensives against the Tainos that culminated in the Battle of Yagüecas.<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/saju/historyculture/upload/A Historical Overview of Colonial Puerto Rico_The Importance of San Juan as a Military Outpost.doc ''A Historical Overview of Colonial Puerto Rico: The Importance of San Juan as a Military Outpost.'']{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} National Park Service. San Juan National Historic Site. History and Culture. no date. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref>
[[File:Parque Monumento Agüeybaná II, El Bravo, en Ponce, Puerto Rico (DSC02669).jpg|thumb|left|220px|The Agüeybaná II ("El Bravo") Park in Ponce, Puerto Rico]]
==Death== In 1511, in the region known as Yagüecas some 11,000 to 15,000 Taínos had assembled against some 80 to 100 Spaniards.<ref name="d" /> Before the start of the battle, a Spanish soldier using an [[arquebus]] shot and killed a native.<ref name="e">[https://books.google.com/books?id=nkYAMSusYKkC&pg=PA4 ''Caciques and Cemí Idols: The Web Spun by Taíno Rulers Between Hispaniola and Puerto Rico.''] José R. Oliver. The University of Alabama Press. 2009. Page 4. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> It is presumed this was Agüeybaná II, because the warrior was wearing a golden necklace which only a cacique wore.<ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:4r3v-f9cKtEJ:humanidades.uprrp.edu/smjeg/reserva/Historia/hist3242/Prof%2520Francisco%2520Moscoso/Mito%2520muerte%2520Agueybana.pdf+muerte+de+agueybana+II&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiiDAt0PHd3-G16f0FSo3sK0rU48GjyYrRtry60WZ03Dm750v6Q9a_MbgdaqBjo64siZp4-7ZwG7gK-inscKwPjJX9E9-B6S5HLjffS7swX9go-uakjk5f4gpm8BI9c8EVjFej9&sig=AHIEtbTcryumeyJz-_-KYZ60l3XhSLU5dg ''El Mito de la Muerte de Agueybana: y de los Caciques Colaboradoes Caguax y Don Alfonso.''] Francisco Moscoso. Revista ICP. Year 10. Number 20. Page 46. 2011. Retrieved 27 December 2012.</ref>
==Aftermath of the battle== After the death of Agüeybaná II, the native warriors retracted and became disorganized.<ref name="d" /> Agüeybaná II's followers opted for engaging the Spaniards via guerilla tactics.<ref name="d" /> Such [[guerilla warfare]] rebellion lasted for next 8 years, until 1519.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=nkYAMSusYKkC&pg=PA4 ''Caciques and Cemí Idols: The Web Spun by Taíno Rulers Between Hispaniola and Puerto Rico.''] José R. Oliver. The University of Alabama Press. 2009. Pages 4, 41. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> A second round of raids erupted in 1513 when Ponce de Leon departed the island to explore Florida. The settlement of [[Caparra Archaeological Site|Caparra]], the seat of the island government at that time, was sacked and burned by an alliance between Taínos and natives from the northeastern Antilles.<ref name="e" />
By 1520 the Taíno presence in the Island had almost disappeared. A government census in 1530 reports the existence of only 1,148 Taínos remaining in Puerto Rico.<ref>[http://www.yale.edu/gsp/colonial/puerto-rico/index.html ''Puerto Rico.''] Yale University. Genocide Studies Program. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> However, oppressive conditions for the surviving Taíno continued. Many of those who stayed on the island soon died of either the cruel treatment that they had received or of the [[smallpox]] epidemic, which had attacked the island in 1519.<ref name="a" /><ref>[http://www.extranews.net/news.php?nid=1796 Puerto Rico's First People] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231030313/http://www.extranews.net/news.php?nid=1796 |date=December 31, 2007 }}</ref>
==Legacy== [[File:Placa en el Parque Monumento Agüeybaná II, El Bravo, en Ponce, Puerto Rico (DSC02667).jpg|thumb|right|300px|Plaque at Agüeybaná II ("El Bravo") Park in sector Caracoles, Barrio Playa, Ponce, Puerto Rico]]
Agüeybaná II is admired in Puerto Rico for his loyalty to his people. Puerto Rico has named many public buildings and streets after him: * The City of [[Bayamón, Puerto Rico|Bayamón]] has named a high school after him. * There is a street in [[Caguas, Puerto Rico|Caguas]] that honors him. * An avenue in the Hato Rey area of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]] is named after Agüeybaná. * Puerto Rico once had an equivalent to the [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] which was awarded annually and was called the "Agüeybaná de Oro" (The Golden Agüeybaná), in honor of the great cacique.<ref>[http://www.musicofpuertorico.com/index.php/artists/el_gran_combo/ ''El Gran Combo.''] Music of Puerto Rico. (Reference to the "Agüeybaná de Oro".) Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref> * In the "Caracoles" sector of barrio [[Playa (Ponce)|Playa]] in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]], [[Puerto Rico]], there is a small park with [[Agüeybaná El Bravo (statue)|a statue depicting Agüeybaná II, "El Bravo" (The Brave)]]. It is located on the southeast corner of the intersection of Ponce By-pass ([[Puerto Rico Highway 2|PR-2]]) and Avenida Hostos ([[PR-123]]). * Poet Daniel de Rivera composed a poem titled ''"Agüeybaná El Bravo"'' dedicated to him. It partially reads:<ref>Socorro Giron. ''Ponce, el Teatro La Perla, y la Campana de la Almudaina.'' Gobierno Municipal de Ponce. Ponce, Puerto Rico. 1992. Page 71. LOC Number: 85-90989.</ref> {| border=0 |- | valign=top | :''"¡Ea, compañeros! Vamos al combate:'' :''Honor la patria a defender nos llama;'' :''Si en paz, contento el corazón no late'' :''La guerra nos dará fortuna y fama;'' :''Hasta la mar que nuestra costa bate'' :''Ondas escupe y agitada brama,'' :''Que cual nosotros contemplar quisiera'' :''Libre esta perla de la gente ibera."'' | valign=top | ::"Hey brothers! Let's go to the fight: ::The motherland calls us to defend our honor; ::If our hearts do not beat peacefully ::War will grant us fortune and fame; ::Even the sea that beats our shores ::Spits waves and rumbles with alarm, ::For like us it, too, would like to see ::Our pearl freed from the Iberian people."'' |}
